Okay, I think the problems with 2D rendering were actually due to me not account for the global 2D viewport in the viewport code. Which is another reason why I should change my approach to the global viewport. I think this is exactly why Godot uses a global 'canvas' for 2D rendering.

All right, I thought my engine was fucked with the resizing and camera spaces but that's actually similar to Godot... well, one of the methods it uses. See, Godot lets you change its stretch mode, aspect, scale, and scale mode; setting the mode to 'disabled' and the aspect to 'ignore' will cause the window to behave like my engine does, currently. I need to implement stretch modes as well as change how I handle the global viewport. Godot uses a root viewport as an abstraction of the global viewport (e.g: `glViewport`); I think I'll do the same and implement these stretch modes into the debugger and see what happens. It's important to note that while I *think* this can be updated while the game is running, stretch modes that retain aspect ratios rely on the root viewport's initial size.

